qx|17B02,THE HONOR SEQUENCE LENGTH LEAD|
nt||HT|e|Va|6|cs|1|cp|4|fp||3d|3|at|^-{    THE HONOR-SEQUENCE LENGTH     }
^-|cp||fp||at|^b@2^Y@3When holding four cards or more of a suit headed by three honors in sequence, or by two honors in sequence and the third card not more than one step lower, the top card |cp|8|at|(except when it is the Ace)|cp||at| should always be led.|FP|2|CP|8|AT|*|CP||FP||AT| Partner may then readily infer that you hold the next two lower cards in the suit, or the next lower card and the third not more than one rank lower. If you lead anything but the top card from such a sequence, Partner will be more or less in the dark about your holding in that suit. The top card, if consistently led, will give Partner definite information right away. 

|CP|8|FP|2|AT|* |CP||FP||AT|^*IIn the present discussion, "lead" must always be taken to mean "opening lead," and any reference to leading is meant to apply to the first lead of the deal.|
PG| ***** 25 ***** |


AT|

For example, in the following suit holdings the card in BOLD RED should be led:
|at|^f@2
@s|cp|8|at|^*BK^*N|cp||at| Q J 3 2|cp|8|at|^*B^k(K)^*N|cp||at|
@c|cp|8|at|^*BQ^*N|CP||at| J 10 3 2|cp|8|at|^*B^k(Q)^*N|cp||at|
