qx|17B03a,Leads From Ace-King Suits|HT|e|Va|6|cs|1|cp|4|fp||3d|3|at|^-{    LEADS FROM ACE-KING SUITS    }
^-|CP||FP||AT|^b@2^Y@3A suit headed by Ace-King presents one of the most difficult problems in defending against no-trump. Some excellent players recommend the lead of the King first if the suit contains four or more cards; others recommend the lead of a low card even when  such a suit contains six cards (provided the Queen and Jack are not also held.)  With Ace-King alone, or Ace-King and one small card, it is just as well, generally speaking, not to select the suit for the opening lead, for the simple reason that your shortness in the suit indicates that the Declarer may have length in it, and you will only aid him to set up his suit. Furthermore, these cards may prove to be valuable entries to your longer suit.|
PG| ***** 37 ***** |


AT| Consider the following Ace-King combinations:

^e1. |IH|pSA(K)Q2|hc|sk|at|      2. |ih|pHAKJ2|hc|Hk|LC|H2|at|    3. |ih|pDAkT9|hc|dk|
pg| ***** 38 ***** |


at|

^b@2With these combinations, whether of four cards or more, the King is generally the best opening lead. |
PG| ***** 39 ***** |


AT|
In No. 1 the advantage is obvious for the Queen can be led to the second round, and control of the suit is retained. |
PG| ***** 40 ***** |


AT|

In No. 2, the King may be led so that if it subsequently develops that Partner can lead through Declarer's Queen, that advantage may be gained. |
PG| ***** 41 ***** |


AT|

In No. 3, the King is led to explore the suit, but the suit is to be discontinued if Declarer seems to hold the Queen, for then Partner's Jack can be led through and the Queen captured.|
PG| ***** 42 ***** |


NT||
%%% 5 continued
HT|e|Va|6|cs|1|cp|4|fp||3d|3|at|^-{    LEADS FROM ACE-KING SUITS    }
^-|CP||FP||AT|^b@2^Y@3With practically all other combinations of four or more cards, of which the top two cards are the Ace and King, the best lead is usually a low card. The low card is sent out to reconnoiter, as it were, while you still have two sure stoppers in the suit. If Partner holds Queen, the whole suit may be established at once.|
PG| ***** 43 ***** |


AT|

In Ace-King suits the proper lead is never the top card of the sequence. This is the only exception to the rule that the top card sequence should be led. If you wonder how your Partner is going to tell from your King lead whether you hold the Queen or the Ace since the King may be led from either sort of sequence, the answer is that your Partner probably cannot tell unless he holds the missing card himself. However, he should be satisfied with the information that you hold either the Ace or Queen, and he will know before long which one you have - or, if he cannot deduce it after a while, he is not the sort of player you will want for a Partner over any great length of time.|
PG| ***** 44 ***** |


