%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% 6) 17B03b
qx|17B03b,Continuation Honor Lead|HT|e|Va|6|cs|1|cp|4|fp||3d|3|at|^-{    CONTINUATION HONOR LEAD    }
^-|CP||FP||ht|g|AT|^b@2^Y@3With honor combinations such as ^i|IH|pSAKQ|at|^m  |IH|pSKQj|at|^r  |IH|pSQJT|ht|m|FP|1|at|^m^*B, ^q, or ^v,|FP||
pg| ***** 45 ***** |


AT| the problem very often arises as to the proper procedure if your first card led holds the trick. For instance, which should you continue from @S A K Q after your King has won? As a rule, it pays to lead the card which gives Partner the maximum amount of information. In the @S A K Q instance, the Queen is the best continuation, because the lead of the Ace the second time fails to tell Partner anything about the location of the Queen, while the lead of the Queen informs Partner definitely (except under certain desperation circumstances) that the Ace is held.|
PG| ***** 46 ***** |


AT|

The reason for the above is apparent when the same principle is applied to the lower honor combinations. With a holding of @S K Q J, for example, the King should be opened and the Jack continued. This card affirms the possession of the Queen. Similarly, from @S Q J 10, the opening of the Queen and continuance of the Ten shows the Jack.|
PG| ***** 47 ***** |


